flex","Contains striated muscle fibres","Contains smooth muscle fibres only","Relaxes in response to gastric distension"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eupper oesophageal sphincter contains striated muscle fibres\u003C/strong\u003E and is formed primarily by the cricopharyngeus muscle. This sphincter is normally closed but briefly relaxes during swallowing to allow food passage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains smooth muscle fibres only\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the lower oesophageal sphincter\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains constant tonic contraction\u003C/strong\u003E - While there is resting tone, it must relax during swallowing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelaxes in response to gastric distension\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a feature of the lower oesophageal sphincter\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContracts during the swallowing reflex\u003C/strong\u003E - The sphincter must relax, not contract, to allow food passage\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe upper oesophageal sphincter is under voluntary control via the vagus nerve, while the lower oesophageal sphincter is controlled by the autonomic nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The upper oesophageal sphincter consists of striated muscle that relaxes during swallowing to allow food passage.","The lower oesophageal sphincter consists of smooth muscle that maintains basal tone to prevent reflux.","Peristaltic waves in the oesophagus are coordinated by the swallowing centre in the medulla."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55303"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17252"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55303"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T20:55:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T20:56:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9942"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69847"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relation